And after all this is but a momentary reminiscence of the prophetie end of the sixth Aeneid.

Milton, in the first book of Paradise Lost, fol- lows the Virgilian, not the Homeric, method. The heathen gods and devils whom he marshals against the hosts of Jehovah are carefully chosen, limited in number, marked by characteristics familiar to his Puritan readers, and poetically distinct and attrac- tive, eg:

‘⁴ Thammuz came next behind, VVhose annual wound in Lebanon allured The Syrian damsels to lament his fate In amorous (litties all a summer's day, While smooth Adonis from his native rock

Ran purple to the sea, supposed with blood Of Thammuz yearly wounded. . .’'2

It is most interesting to notice that Milton had much the same difficulty to face as Virgil, and that he dealt with it victoriously in the very same way.
